owl:Ontology.dc:creator: HL7 Security and CBCC Work Groups
owl:Ontology.dc:description: This ontology currently represents core HL7 Security and Privacy concepts.
owl:Ontology.dc:source: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy Domain Analysis Model, May, 2010.
HL7 Healthcare Privacy and Security Classification System (HCS)
ISO/TS 21298: Health informatics — Functional and structural roles
ISO/TS 22600 Health informatics – Privilege management and access control, 2006.
owl:Ontology.dc:subject: HL7
Privacy
Security
owl:Ontology.dc:title: SecurityAndPrivacyOntologyOntology

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: May eliminate this specialization of the authorizedBy property.
May eliminate this specialization of the authorizedBy property.
May eliminate this specialization of the authorizedBy property.
May eliminate this specialization of the authorizedBy property.

owl:ObjectProperty.dc:description: Describes constraint(s) within the scope of a catalog.
Relates a constraint policy to a policy it constrains.
Describes exercise of control over a type of information reference.
Exercises control over a type of operation.
Describes exercise of control for a purpose.
Describes exercise of control over a type of role.
Describes role(s) included within a set.
Describes user assignment(s) included within a set.
Describes roles separated by constraints (in the sense of Role Based Access Control), e.g., for separation of duty reasona.

owl:DatatypeProperty.rdfs:comment: Intended to capture the web location where the document in question is published for human consumption, as opposed to the URI of this ontology element.

owl:Class.dc:description: An authority is an organization (either Jurisdictional or Provider) that is responsible for a Privacy Policy.
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: According to the CSP-DAM: 'This abstract class is used to designate the authority that issues the policy.'
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Authority

owl:Class.dc:description: An authorization policy defines allowed actions.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Authorization Policy

owl:Class.dc:description: A basic security policy serves as a common basis for more specific types of security policies, for example authorization, delegation, obligation and refrain policies.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Basic Security Policy

owl:Class.dc:description: A clearinghouse is an organization that collects, classifies and/or distributes (healthcare) information.
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Description derived from Merriam Webster.
Mentioned in text of CSP-DAM though not specified there as a class.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Clearinghouse

owl:Class.dc:description: A client is a person who is the subject of a consent directive. [HL7 CSP-DAM]
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: The definition of Client is debatable. On the other hand, a client with no consent directive arguably has no impact on access control."
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Client

owl:Class.dc:description: As a part of the service they provide to patients, medical doctors, nurses and allied health workers compile notes that document the conditions they encounter, the treatments provided and the outcomes of those treatments. [U.S. National Library of Medicine; http://www.nlm.nih.gov/nichsr/usestats/clinical_observation.html; Retrieved on July 29, 2013]
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 HCS
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: ClinicalObservation is a generalization of the ClinicalCondition class from the HL7 CSP-DAM.
Subclasses of ClinicalObservation are specified in ClinicalObservationOntology.owl.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Clinical Observation

owl:Class.dc:description: A compartment is a security label tag that "segments" an IT resource by indicating that access and use is restricted to members of a defined community or project.
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 Healthcare Privacy and Security Classification System (HCS)
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Compartment

owl:Class.dc:description: A composite security policy combines other policies (authorization, constraint, delegation, obligation, and/or refrain policies).
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Composite Security Policy

owl:Class.dc:description: Confidentiality is the property that information is not made available or disclosed to unauthorized individuals. [per ISO 7498-2:1989]
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM, which cites ISO 7498-2:1989.
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Subclasses of Confidentiality are specified in ConfidentialityOntology.owl.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Confidentiality

owl:Class.dc:description: A Consenter is a person who is an individual client of healthcare services or a client delegate (Substitute Decision Maker) that uses a computer system to manage client privacy consent directives.
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Consenter

owl:Class.dc:description: A constraint is a restriction (condition or obligation) that is enforced upon access permissions.
owl:Class.dc:source: ANSI/INCITS 359-2004
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: In the future, subclasses of Constraint may be moved to a separate sub-ontology.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Constraint

owl:Class.dc:description: A constraint catalog is a collection of constraints on permissions (as specified by an organization).
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 RBAC Constraint Catalog
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Constraint Catalog

owl:Class.dc:description: A constraint policy places constraints on another policy.
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Constraint Policy

owl:Class.dc:description: The DataOperation class categorizes operations from the perspective of their effect on object(s).
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Subclasses of DataOperation are specified in CRUDEA_OperationOntology.owl and in turn in DataOperationOntology.owl.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Data Operation

owl:Class.dc:description: A delegation policy defines what authorizations can be delegated to whom.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Delegation Policy

owl:Class.dc:description: A functional role reflects functional aspects of relationships between entities. Functional roles are bound to the realization/performance of acts.
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: [taken from HL7 RBAC Role Engineering Process:] Functional Roles consist of all the permissions (operations on health information system objects) needed to perform a task. Functional role names are associated with groups of permissions for convenience in assigning to users.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Functional Role

owl:Class.dc:description: A grantee is a person or organization given privilege(s), e.g., by a delegation policy.
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Grantee

owl:Class.dc:description: A health record stores healthcare information about a person.
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Health Record

owl:Class.dc:description: An information reference is a specification of the attributes of protected information referenced by a policy.
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Information Reference

owl:Class.dc:description: Integrity is the attribute that information is not altered in any way, deliberately or accidentally.
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Made a meaningless change in the wording of the ISO definition, from 'property' to 'attribute' to avoid confusion with OWL properties.
Subclasses of Integrity are specified in IntegrityOntology.owl.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Integrity

owl:Class.dc:description: An interorganizational agreement specifies (security and privacy) arrangements among organizations.
owl:Class.dc:source: 'Refrain Policy Vocabulary' presentation to HL7 Security WG by Kathleen Connor in November 2011.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Interorganizational Agreement

owl:Class.dc:description: A jurisdiction is an area with a set of laws under the control of a system of courts which are different to neighboring areas.
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: In the future, instances of Jurisdiction may be defined in a separate sub-ontology. For now, sample instances are included within SomewhereHospitalOntology.owl.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Jurisdiction

owl:Class.dc:description: A jurisdictional organization is an organization that has territorial authority.
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Jurisdictional Organization

owl:Class.dc:description: A location is a site (such as a physical place or a system, workstation or terminal in a network).
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: It is expected that specific organizations will create and maintain their own subclasses and instances of Location.
Should an Organization have a LocationSet to capture the locations which it may use in policies to control access?
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Location

owl:Class.dc:description: An object is an entity that contains or receives information. An object can represent information containers (e.g., files or directories in an operating system, and/or columns, rows, tables, and views within a database management system) or objects can represent exhaustible system resources, such as printers, disk space, and CPU cycles.
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 RBAC (based on ANSI/INCITS 359-2004)
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Subclasses of Object are specified in ObjectOntology.owl.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Object

owl:Class.dc:description: An obligation represents a resposibility to follow a course of action.
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Subclasses of Obligation are specified in ObligationOntology.owl.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Obligation

owl:Class.dc:description: An obligation policy is event-triggered and defines actions to be performed by manager agents.
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: ISO 22600-2 describes obligation policy in terms of manager agents but says nothing about the latter.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Obligation Policy

owl:Class.dc:description: To operate is to act on an object or objects. An operation is an executable image of a program, which upon invocation executes some function for the user. Within a file system, operations might include read, write, and execute. Within a database management system, operations might include append, delete, and update.
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: For the Security and Privacy Ontology in general, we have adopted 'CamelCase' naming which differd slightly from the HL7 RBAC Permission Catalog and from the HL7 vocabulary repository (which also differ from each other).
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Operation

owl:Class.dc:description: An organization is an administrative and/or functional entity.
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: In the Composite Security and Privacy DAM, a generalization of JurisdictionalOrganization and ProviderOrganization is named 'Authority'. However, ISO 22600-2 defines Authority as 'entity that is responsible for the issuance of certificates'.

It is expected that specific organizations will create and maintain their own sub-ontology which imports SecurityAndPrivacyOntology.owl along with some or all of the accompanying subontologies and adds suitable local instances of classes.
Organization has exactly one role set per conversation with M. Davis et al., 08/24/2010.
Textual description derived from Merriam Webster.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Organization

owl:Class.dc:description: A payment source is the provider of payment for the healthcare services documented by electronic health records.
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Subclasses of PaymentSource are specified in PaymentSourceOntology.owl.
The CSP-DAM names the class PolicyProgramPaymentSource but its decription is strictly in terms of payment.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Payment Source

owl:Class.dc:description: A person is a human being.
owl:Class.dc:source: De novo
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Obvious generalization of Client, Consenter and similar classes.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Person

owl:Class.dc:description: A policy is a set of legal, political, organizational, functional and technical obligations or omissions for communication and cooperation. [ISO 22600-3]
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Policy

owl:Class.dc:description: A population is a subject of privacy policy or consent which is a body of persons or individuals having a quality or characteristic in common.
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Population

owl:Class.dc:description: A privacy consent directive is special policy which defines an agreement between an entity playing the role of the subject of an act and an entity acting. [ISO 22600-3]
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: According to the CSP-DAM: 'A Privacy Consent Directive is defined as 'an instruction regarding consent and contextual conditions to collect, use, and/or disclose Personal Health Information.' This definition is adapted from the British Columbia, E-Health (Personal Health Information Access and Protection of Privacy) Act, S.B.C. 2008, c. 38, s. 1.'
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Privacy Consent Directive

owl:Class.dc:description: The PrivacyOperation class categorizes operations from the perspective of their effect on the privacy of (health) information.
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Subclasses of PrivacyOperation are specified in PrivacyOperationOntology.owl.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Privacy Operation

owl:Class.dc:description: A privacy policy is a policy that is concerned with information privacy practices.
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Privacy Policy

owl:Class.dc:description: A privacy rule specifies permission or obligation to treat information in accord with privacy wishes.
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Privacy Rule

owl:Class.dc:description: A provider organization is an organization that furnishes healthcare.
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Provider Organization

owl:Class.dc:description: A purpose of use is an intention for which an object is accessed.
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Subclasses of PurposeOfUse are specified in PurposeOfUseOntology.owl.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Purpose of Use

owl:Class.dc:description: A refrain represents a responsibility to not follow a course of action.
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 v3 RefrainPolicy value set.
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Subclasses of Refrain are specified in RefrainOntology.owl.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Refrain

owl:Class.dc:description: A refrain policy is a policy used to indicate that a specific action is prohibited based on specific access control attributes (e.g., purpose of use, information type, user role, etc.).
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Refrain Policy

owl:Class.dc:description: A role set is a collection of roles (as specified by an organization).
owl:Class.dc:source: De novo
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Role Set

owl:Class.dc:description: A route is a sequence of links, and/or partial links, that describe a path, usually between two positions, within a network [ISO 19133:2005] [ISO 19134:2007, 4.11]
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Subclasses of Route are specified in RouteOntology.owl.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Route

owl:Class.dc:description: A security policy is a policy that is concerned with information security practices.
A set of rules laid down by the security authority governing the use and provision of security services and facilities [ISO/TS 22600-3:2009(E)]
A set of rules that constrains one or more sets of activities of one or more sets of objects [ISO/IEC 10746-3]
plan or course of action adopted for providing computer security [ISO/TS 22600-1:2006(E), ISO/TS 22600-2:2006(E), and ISO/TS 22600-3:2009(E)]
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: The Composite Security and Privacy DAM has a class named 'Policy' but refers in text to the more specific notion of 'Security Policy'.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Security Policy

owl:Class.dc:description: A role is set of competences and/or performances that are associated with a task.
owl:Class.dc:source: ISO/TS 21298:2008(E) and ANSI/INCITS 359-2004
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: 'Role' is considered a synonym for this 'SecurityRole' class per the 08/24/2010 meeting of the Security WG.
Roles provide a means of indirectly assigning privileges to individuals.
Subclasses of SecurityRole are specified in RoleOntology.owl.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Security Role

owl:Class.dc:description: Sensitivity specifies the characteristic of a resource which implies its value or importance, and may include its vulnerability [ISO 7498-2:1989]. Vulnerability here is defined as medically vulnerable with respect to privacy, subject to social stigmatization.
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Subclasses of Sensitivity are specified in SensitivityOntology.owl.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Sensitivity

owl:Class.dc:description: A separation of duty constraint is a constraint that defines exclusivity relations among roles.
owl:Class.dc:source: ANSI/INCITS 359-2004
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Separation of Duty Constraint

owl:Class.dc:description: A role of a place that further classifies the setting (e.g., accident site, road side, work site, community location) in which services are delivered.
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 v3 ServiceDeliveryLocationRoleType value set
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Subclasses of ServiceDeliveryLocation are specified in ServiceDeliveryLocationOntology.owl.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Service Delivery Location

owl:Class.dc:description: A structural role reflects the structural aspects of relationships between entities. Structural roles describe prerequisites, feasibilities or competences for acts.
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: According to the HL7 CSP-DAM: A structural role is a security role that places a user in an organizational hierarchy as belonging to a category of healthcare personnel warranting certain levels of access control: Structural roles allow users to participate in the organization’s workflow (e.g., tasks) by job, title, or position, but do not specify detailed permissions on specific information objects. Structural roles allow a user to “connect” to a resource, but do not grant authorizations.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Structural Role

owl:Class.dc:description: A subject of [a] record is a person or population described by a health record (record object).
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM
owl:Class.rdfs:label: Subject of Record

owl:Class.dc:description: A user assignment is an association of a user with role(s) he or she is allowed to assume.
owl:Class.dc:source: ANSI/INCITS 359-2004
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: It is expected that specific organizations will create and maintain their own instances of UserAssignment.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: User Assignment

owl:Class.dc:description: A user assignment set is a collection of assignments of users to roles (as specified by an organization).
owl:Class.dc:source: De novo
owl:Class.rdfs:label: User Assignment Set

owl:Class.dc:description: A user identity is the representation of a human being in an information system.
owl:Class.dc:source: HL7 Composite Security and Privacy DAM
owl:Class.rdfs:label: User Identity
